WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.160
Hello, everyone. Thank you for coming to my talk. I'll just get running and rolling here.

00:00:12.160 --> 00:00:18.799
If you'd like to follow along as I go through this, you can find the slides on the conference

00:00:18.799 --> 00:00:23.559
app for this speaker session. I also just tweeted out the link. You can find that at

00:00:23.559 --> 00:00:31.280
markjrieke, that's I-E-K-E. But today, I'll be introducing Workboots, which is a tool

00:00:31.280 --> 00:00:38.400
and a package for generating prediction intervals from tidymodel workflows. So I used to be

00:00:38.400 --> 00:00:43.320
a mechanical engineer. So before I jump into talking about this tool, I want to talk about

00:00:43.320 --> 00:00:52.639
some other niche and interesting tools that I've seen as a mechanical engineer.

00:00:52.639 --> 00:00:57.400
So this is something interesting. If you look at it, you might not know what it's used for

00:00:57.400 --> 00:01:02.639
offhand. One of my friends who works at AB sent this to me. This is a pigtail-proof coil.

00:01:02.639 --> 00:01:09.480
It lets brewers take samples from these humongous beer tanks safely.

00:01:09.480 --> 00:01:15.519
The second tool, again, really interesting-looking. What's it used for off the bat? I don't know.

00:01:15.519 --> 00:01:19.559
But for folks who do know, this is a wire crimper, and it's very useful for dealing

00:01:19.559 --> 00:01:26.879
with large electrical lugs, again, safely and efficiently. And this abomination, we

00:01:26.879 --> 00:01:35.080
don't really have to talk about too much. But one tool that I use often that is, again,

00:01:35.080 --> 00:01:40.000
niche and specific is this Kreg jig. On first glance, you might not know what it would be

00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:47.839
used for. It's got this odd cylinder on one side. But you can see that in a specific scenario,

00:01:47.839 --> 00:01:53.519
it's a perfect tool for this job. And that's kind of what I like to think of

00:01:53.519 --> 00:02:00.760
Workboots as. It is a specific tool for a specific job. And that specific job is for

00:02:00.760 --> 00:02:06.519
when you are building a model and you would like to generate a prediction interval, but

00:02:06.519 --> 00:02:12.039
you're using a model type that on its own only generates point predictions. Workboots

00:02:12.039 --> 00:02:19.000
will let you take that model and generate prediction intervals.

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:25.080
So why might you be interested in using this package? Well, maybe you're somebody like

00:02:25.080 --> 00:02:31.000
me. Again, my name is Mark Rieke. I am a Senior Consumer Experience Analyst for Memorial

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:37.679
Hermann Health System in Houston, Texas. We are a large hospital system in the Houston

00:02:37.679 --> 00:02:46.279
area with 17 hospitals, 11 of which are acute care, hundreds of clinics and outpatient facilities,

00:02:46.279 --> 00:02:53.759
servicing about 30,000 employees. And my small but mighty team of four handles and fields

00:02:53.759 --> 00:02:58.759
requests from all 30,000 employees. So to the other team members who are keeping the

00:02:58.759 --> 00:03:04.699
fort together, I'm very thankful that they let me run off to D.C.

00:03:04.699 --> 00:03:12.039
But what we do is we deal with our patient satisfaction survey data. Our job is to administer,

00:03:12.039 --> 00:03:18.759
understand, analyze this data to hopefully improve our patient satisfaction when they

00:03:18.759 --> 00:03:24.759
go through our hospital system. And the majority of the time, our day-to-day involves answering

00:03:24.759 --> 00:03:31.080
questions. So some of the questions that come up are ones like this. We see a pretty consistent

00:03:31.080 --> 00:03:37.199
trend going upwards in our patient satisfaction score and then this drop off in April. What's

00:03:37.199 --> 00:03:44.399
going on there? If we look at scores across hospitals, maybe we're seeing differences.

00:03:44.399 --> 00:03:50.360
Are these real differences or is this just due to sampling variation?

00:03:50.360 --> 00:03:56.139
And thirdly, we see different response rates depending on if we send invites out via email

00:03:56.139 --> 00:04:02.600
or if we send invites out via text. Which one should we use? So these are all questions

00:04:02.600 --> 00:04:09.600
that on their own, giving a point estimate for, you know, is a good first step. But to

00:04:09.600 --> 00:04:15.039
get the full picture, we really need to add in uncertainty because that will help us separate

00:04:15.039 --> 00:04:22.679
signal from noise. So maybe we see by adding in confidence intervals that in April, perhaps

00:04:22.679 --> 00:04:27.799
there was a disruption in the survey distribution workflow and we only sent out a few surveys

00:04:27.799 --> 00:04:32.600
that month. So this is really just statistical noise.

00:04:32.600 --> 00:04:39.000
You know, if we look across hospitals, maybe we see a lot of overlap in the potential underlying

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:45.720
scores. So again, you know, nothing to be too concerned about here. But hey, if we look

00:04:45.720 --> 00:04:49.320
at the difference in response rates, these are pretty significantly different and it's

00:04:49.320 --> 00:04:53.440
readily apparent once we add in our uncertainty intervals. And this is something that we can

00:04:53.440 --> 00:04:58.279
action around. I think when I say this out loud, we all understand

00:04:58.279 --> 00:05:03.779
at a base level that point estimates don't give the full picture. But we really need

00:05:03.779 --> 00:05:08.579
additional context to help that point sink through.

00:05:08.579 --> 00:05:13.220
So this also extends to not just when I'm answering specific questions, but when I'm

00:05:13.220 --> 00:05:19.940
answering questions with a model. So, you know, what are the drivers of patient satisfaction?

00:05:19.940 --> 00:05:24.579
What will our score be? How many responses are we expecting? These are all questions

00:05:24.579 --> 00:05:29.660
that I can and have answered with models. But again, because I'm always wanting to layer

00:05:29.660 --> 00:05:35.339
in uncertainty, I'm really limited to the types of models that I can use.

00:05:35.339 --> 00:05:42.500
My problem is that this is me, like, all the time. I see people using, like, fun and fancy

00:05:42.500 --> 00:05:52.660
models like XGBoost, but because of the work I'm doing, I'm stuck using plain old LM.

00:05:52.660 --> 00:05:56.940
So that's where Workboots comes into play. This is a package that hopefully bridges the

00:05:56.940 --> 00:06:02.380
gap between simpler models that let you generate prediction intervals right out of the bag

00:06:02.380 --> 00:06:09.700
and more powerful models that let you, you know, get nonlinearity and complex interactions.

00:06:09.700 --> 00:06:13.299
Workboots hopefully gets the best of both worlds by letting you generate prediction

00:06:13.299 --> 00:06:19.660
intervals while still using your more powerful models.

00:06:19.660 --> 00:06:26.779
So let's go into the package itself. And I think one thing we should do right out

00:06:26.779 --> 00:06:31.619
the gate is look at where Workboots sits in the model building timeline. If some of

00:06:31.619 --> 00:06:35.700
you recognize this slide, this is something that I totally stole from an old Julia Silgi

00:06:35.700 --> 00:06:42.859
presentation that walks through how you might go from model conception and idea to model

00:06:42.859 --> 00:06:49.299
finalization. So maybe you're starting off on the left with doing some exploratory analysis,

00:06:49.299 --> 00:06:55.820
engineering new features, and then fitting, tuning, and evaluating a set of models. And

00:06:55.820 --> 00:07:03.579
perhaps you repeat this a few times before you finally get to your finalized model.

00:07:03.579 --> 00:07:09.260
A lot of this is already handled by tidy models. Workboots really just comes in as that last

00:07:09.260 --> 00:07:15.339
leg of the journey. So you've done all your preprocessing, done all your feature engineering,

00:07:15.339 --> 00:07:18.540
you know, all of your hyperparameters are tuned. And now you're ready to answer that

00:07:18.540 --> 00:07:22.380
big question that your stakeholder has been asking you.

00:07:22.380 --> 00:07:27.179
And part of the reason why it makes sense that Workboots is, you know, just this last

00:07:27.179 --> 00:07:32.500
step is that there are a couple of checks that you really want to make sure you're hitting

00:07:32.500 --> 00:07:37.459
before it makes sense to use Workboots. Again, it's a really specific tool for a really specific

00:07:37.459 --> 00:07:45.239
job. So firstly, you should make sure that the residuals of your model are normally distributed.

00:07:45.239 --> 00:07:49.619
This is an assumption that it makes under the hood. Secondly, you need to make sure

00:07:49.619 --> 00:07:55.220
you actually have enough time to run this model. I'm an analyst. I wrote this for myself

00:07:55.220 --> 00:08:01.820
primarily. I'm never really concerned with putting models into production. So depending

00:08:01.820 --> 00:08:06.700
on the amount of preprocessing and the size of your data set, Workboots could take anywhere

00:08:06.700 --> 00:08:13.820
between 5 and 20 minutes to output prediction intervals. So please do not deploy this when

00:08:13.820 --> 00:08:18.859
you need to have something answer a question in a fraction of a second.

00:08:18.859 --> 00:08:24.420
And thirdly and finally, most importantly, it really makes sense to make sure that you

00:08:24.420 --> 00:08:29.320
actually need this more powerful model that Workboots allows you to use. What I found

00:08:29.320 --> 00:08:35.419
a lot of the time is that good old plain Jane LM will, you know, really get you the answers

00:08:35.419 --> 00:08:41.960
that you need maybe 80, 90% of the time. But if you do find yourself in a scenario where

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:46.479
you are meeting all three of these checks and you're ready to start using Workboots,

00:08:46.479 --> 00:08:52.119
how does it actually work? I'm going to gloss over this very quickly, but if you'd like

00:08:52.119 --> 00:08:57.479
to dig in deeper into some of the math that's underlying it, you can scan this QR code.

00:08:57.479 --> 00:09:03.039
That'll take you to a little bit of an explainer. But at a very high level, Workboots takes

00:09:03.039 --> 00:09:11.200
your training data, generates a whole bunch of bootstrap resamples, then it fits many

00:09:11.239 --> 00:09:16.559
models to each of these resamples. Or excuse me, it fits a model to each resample so that

00:09:16.559 --> 00:09:22.559
you end up with many models. Thirdly, it takes each of these many models and predicts on

00:09:22.559 --> 00:09:28.880
new data. So for each observation in your new dataset, you have many predictions. And

00:09:28.880 --> 00:09:37.280
then finally, it summarizes all of these with a prediction range.

00:09:37.280 --> 00:09:41.960
So now that we've checked that we can use Workboots, we kind of know what's going on,

00:09:41.960 --> 00:09:46.119
let's get into actually using it with some code. So there's three things that we're going

00:09:46.119 --> 00:09:51.679
to do. First of all, Workboots builds on top of tidy models. So what we'll do is set up

00:09:51.679 --> 00:09:59.200
a tidy model workflow. Next, we'll use Workboots to generate our predictions. And then thirdly,

00:09:59.200 --> 00:10:08.080
we'll use Workboots to summarize these results. There is some great documentation on tidy

00:10:08.080 --> 00:10:14.320
models and how to use it. But I will just set up a very quick workflow for explanation's

00:10:14.320 --> 00:10:22.880
sake. So in this case, we'll be using the Palmer penguins dataset for this example.

00:10:22.880 --> 00:10:27.400
This is a dataset that contains a bunch of information and characteristics about penguins

00:10:27.719 --> 00:10:34.520
from different islands, such as their bill length, bill depth, what species they are,

00:10:34.520 --> 00:10:38.280
which island they came from, and what we'll be predicting on their body mass.

00:10:40.840 --> 00:10:44.919
As is best practice for this example, we'll split into a testing and training dataset.

00:10:48.359 --> 00:10:54.359
So next, we'll set up a pretty basic preprocessing recipe. In this case, again, we'll be predicting

00:10:54.359 --> 00:10:58.679
each penguin's body mass based on all of the data that's available in the dataset.

00:11:00.760 --> 00:11:06.200
And then we'll combine this preprocessing with a model in a workflow. In this case,

00:11:06.200 --> 00:11:12.520
using a boosted tree model for regression, which uses XGBoost under the hood. As a reminder,

00:11:12.520 --> 00:11:19.320
XGBoost can only generate point predictions on its own. So now that we have the workflow set up,

00:11:20.119 --> 00:11:22.280
we're done with tidy models. Now we can jump into work boots.

00:11:26.039 --> 00:11:32.359
One of the large workhorse functions within the package is this predict boots function. This is

00:11:33.239 --> 00:11:38.280
going to take the workflow that we just set up. We'll pass that to predict boots.

00:11:39.239 --> 00:11:48.280
Specify the number of bootstrap resamples that we'd like to take. And then because we are fitting

00:11:48.280 --> 00:11:53.880
and predicting all in one fell swoop, we're going to pass both the training data and the

00:11:53.880 --> 00:11:57.880
new data that we're going to predict on. In this case, this is the penguin's test dataset.

00:11:59.880 --> 00:12:07.080
And what this returns is a table with nested predictions for each observation in the test

00:12:07.080 --> 00:12:13.880
dataset. So in this case, each row is a penguin in penguin's test, and we have 2,000 estimations of

00:12:13.880 --> 00:12:19.400
their weight from our many models that we created. We can summarize this by passing this

00:12:19.400 --> 00:12:26.280
to the summarize predictions function. This just returns a median, lower, and upper prediction

00:12:26.280 --> 00:12:32.359
interval range. And just like that, we have taken a model that only generates point predictions

00:12:33.080 --> 00:12:37.000
and returned prediction ranges. Excuse me, prediction intervals.

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:48.200
By default, work boots and predict boots will generate prediction intervals. But if we so

00:12:48.200 --> 00:12:53.400
desire, we can change this to generate confidence intervals by setting interval to confidence.

00:12:54.520 --> 00:12:59.719
And just as a reminder of the difference between the two, here's an example looking at the AIMS

00:12:59.719 --> 00:13:06.599
housing dataset. In this case, this example is predicting each home's sale price based on the

00:13:06.599 --> 00:13:12.280
first floor square footage. On the left, prediction intervals are the range in which we might expect

00:13:12.280 --> 00:13:18.520
to find any individual home's price. And on the right is an example of a confidence interval,

00:13:18.520 --> 00:13:21.559
which is the range in which we might expect to find the model output.

00:13:26.359 --> 00:13:30.679
Thirdly and finally, in addition to generating prediction and confidence intervals,

00:13:30.679 --> 00:13:34.679
work boots allows us to generate estimations of variable importance.

00:13:36.440 --> 00:13:42.200
This function that does this is very similar to predict boots. It takes the workflow that

00:13:42.200 --> 00:13:49.000
we've created, passes it to VI boots. We specify, again, the number of resamples that we'd like to

00:13:49.000 --> 00:13:58.599
take and give it our training data. And what this returns is a table with nested estimations of

00:13:58.599 --> 00:14:05.479
variable importance for each feature in the model. And what we can see from this example

00:14:07.239 --> 00:14:13.640
oops, sorry, missed a slide. And again, there's another summarize function that lets us return a

00:14:13.640 --> 00:14:20.200
median lower and upper interval range. We can pass this to summarize importance to get this output.

00:14:21.640 --> 00:14:27.559
And what we can see from this example is that flipper length and whether this species was,

00:14:27.640 --> 00:14:33.239
you know, of the gen two species is pretty important to this XGBoost or this set of

00:14:33.239 --> 00:14:39.000
XGBoost models in determining each penguin's weight. But there are wide ranges around those

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:44.039
estimations of importance. And the other hand, what island the penguin comes from

00:14:44.760 --> 00:14:52.359
is we're pretty confident it's not very important. So in closing, my call to action for you all

00:14:52.359 --> 00:14:59.880
is to give Workboots a shot. Again, I think this is a very specific tool for a very specific job.

00:15:00.760 --> 00:15:07.000
But if you find yourself in the situation where you need to generate prediction intervals and

00:15:07.000 --> 00:15:11.080
you don't want to be limited by model type, I think Workboots might be the package for you.

00:15:11.799 --> 00:15:18.919
So thank you. I'm happy to take any questions. I have some links for additional reading material

00:15:18.919 --> 00:15:24.280
that'll if you're interested in digging in further. Thank you.

